        "id": 1000153
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-07-13T18:30:10Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Every spi flash is laid out differently.  The original intent here was to capture that so that partial updates, verification, and decommissioning could be done.\n\nAgreed, \"BIOS\" is too generic of a term, as is \"HOST\".  I suspect we need to follow the existing pattern here with \u003cmanufacturername\u003eSpiFlash.",
      "parentUuid": "65191724_61f8a6cd",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 7,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 11,
        "endChar": 36
      },
      "revId": "7ededf61f85edc96ebb92629c6e4b031ba5d8eea",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "b51f50f0_78085941",
        "filename": "/COMMIT_MSG",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 11,
      "author": {
        "id": 1000000
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-07-13T19:54:08Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Should we handle that through Compatible?  It seems like it is slow to add new schema entries but is less work to add a new Compatible or similar.\n\n@paligill@gmail.com - What have we been doing for CPLDs, etc?  It\u0027d be good to move towards some consistency.",
      "parentUuid": "72b3b529_7c7b0b0a",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 7,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 11,
        "endChar": 36
      },
      "revId": "7ededf61f85edc96ebb92629c6e4b031ba5d8eea",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "4d2ac474_d31a4a91",
        "filename": "/COMMIT_MSG",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 11,
      "author": {
        "id": 1002484
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-07-14T01:53:05Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Hi @patrick@stwcx.xyz and @ed@tanous.net, thanks for the feedback.\n\nRegarding CPLDs, the current schema handles them by explicitly defining every supported vendor and chip in the Type enum using a \u003cvendor\u003e\u003cchip\u003eFirmware pattern (e.g., \"LatticeLCMXO3D_4300Firmware\", \"AlteraMAX10_10M16Firmware\").\n\nI completely agree that \"HOST\" and \"BIOS\" are too generic to capture the specific flash layouts and validation logic required for different devices.\n\nShould we follow the highly specific structure currently used by CPLDs and add \u003cManufacturer\u003eSpiFlash directly to the schema enum?\n\nCurrently, We rely on the explicit Type enum to lock onto specific devices and trigger customized behaviors such as version get.",
      "parentUuid": "b51f50f0_78085941",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 7,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 11,
        "endChar": 36
      },
      "revId": "7ededf61f85edc96ebb92629c6e4b031ba5d8eea",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "047833c0_47815dcb",
        "filename": "/COMMIT_MSG",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 11,
      "author": {
        "id": 1001758
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-07-14T02:07:32Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "@patrick@stwcx.xyz The compatible is there for comparing the PLDM image compatible image only. For general flows we rely on the EM type, so its better to follow the similar approach here.\n\n@Kyle.Hsieh@quantatw.com We need a way to check if this a Host SPI Flash or something else, for example Intel NIC one you are trying to add (as FW version read logic can vary depending on chip not just manufacturer) so its better if we use the \u003cvendor\u003e\u003cchip\u003eSpiFlash nomenclature format here. For BIOS, you can replace the Chip with Host for clarity.",
      "parentUuid": "4d2ac474_d31a4a91",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 7,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 11,
        "endChar": 36
      },
      "revId": "7ededf61f85edc96ebb92629c6e4b031ba5d8eea",
